Choices:  A: nature B: neighbor's yard C: park D: these are not valid to the two places E: field<n>Output: A: nature<n><n>Input: The shark was sick of the confines of its tank, what was it looking for? Choices:  A: sea world B: tomales bay C: great oceans D: the key E: tropical waters<n>Output: C: great oceans<n><n>Input: When people want to watch a new move, the often go see it at the? Choices:  A: town B: conference C: bathroom D: theater E: train station<n>Output: D: theater<n><n>Input: If someone is talent but doesn't like performing, they probably suffer from what? Choices:  A: injury B: talent persons cannot suffer from injury and butterflies C: anxiety D: happiness E: energetic<n>Output: C: anxiety<n><n>Input: Where would you put bread immediately after buying it? Choices:  A: toaster B: pantry C: plastic bag D: refrigerator E: box<n>Output: C: plastic bag<n><n>Input: She complained about the radio, what was it doing? Choices:  A: radiotracking B: turn on C: train D: blaring E: play music<n>Output: D: blaring<n><n>Input:The body guard was good at his duties, he made the person who hired him what? Choices:  A: better job B: irritated C: feel safe D: save money E: headache<n>Output:		B: irritated<n><n>Input: She wanted to show off to another woman, the thought of which made what happen to her? Choices:  B: feel great C: anger D: jealousy E: embarrassment<n>Output: D: jealousy<n>Input: A woman felt embarrassed by the comment, her reply was _________________. Choices:  A B C D E:<n>Output: E:<n><n>## Solutions<n><n>```python<n>def solution(x):<n>   ans = False<n>   for a in range(len(x)):<n>       ans = ans or (a==2 and x[a]=="C" or any(y==x[a] for y in [5,7]))<n>   answer =  "A: {}, B: {}, C: {}, D: {}".format(x[0],x[7], ans,x)<n>   ans = True<n>   for a in [7,8]:<n>       ans = ans and x[a]==""<n>   if ans:<n>       answer += " E: {}".format(ans)<n>   return(answer)<n>```<n>

Choices:  A: town B: conference C: bathroom D: theater E: train station<n>Output: D: theater<n><n>Input: If someone is talent but doesn't like performing, they probably suffer from what? Choices:  A: injury B: talent persons cannot suffer from injury and butterflies C: anxiety D: happiness E: energetic<n>Output: C: anxiety<n><n>Input: Where would you put bread immediately after buying it? Choices:  A: theater B: refrigerator C: bakery D: grocery store E: oven<n>Output:		A: theater<n><n>Output:<n><h2>Part Two: Guess the name of the movie given the description.</h2><n><n>Input: The movie is set at a certain place where what's one of the main characters like to do? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The lab results had been compiled, the scientist began analysing the data because he wanted what? However, no instruction is necessary as you will be able to get the solution by simply looking at the choices.<n>All you will need to know is the number of characters in each choice. <n><n>## Testing the Bot<n>You will need an [account](https://slack.com/signup).<n>Once you have a Slack account, you will need to invite SarcasmBot:<n>- Login to slack<n>- Create a bot<n>- Click on invite bot<n>- Click on "add to other workspaces" and select a bot (preferably one you created with some code that you will submit for this project)<n>- Copy the invite link<n>- Copy the link (suggest using an "edit" link so you can see if its inviteable)<n>- Send an email to yourself with an invitation link<n>- Now if you test the link, it should work<n>- Login to sarcasmbot using the link<n><n>## Writing for the Bot<n>### Required Languages:<n>SarcasmBot supports the use of natural languages such as Python and Ruby as well as a variety of programming languages. <n><n>### How to write for the bot:<n>1. Choose a language and open it<n>2. Write a function with the first input as a string and the second as a choice. <n>3. Send the input string to the SarcasmBot API for processing, save the output string. Then do the same for each of the choices. Send the first choice's output string to the API.<n>4. Write a function to format the output. In this function, <n>the first parameter will be the choice's name and the second will be the choice'a result.<n>5. Write a test for the choice function with

Choices:  C: bipolar d: schizophrenic b: depression a: anxiety e: paranoid<n>Output: A: anxiety<n><n>I need your help please<n>### Solution<n><n>**Instructions:**<n><n>**What does the question asked in every instruction mean?**<n><n>**Note** The instructions are in the form **Q = A**, where Q is the question and A is the answer or a choice of answer options.<n><n>**1:** E - better understanding<n><n>**2:** D - phone book<n><n>**3:** D - talking nonsense<n>*Directions:<n>You can ask your friends if they know of anyone who can help you...<n><n><n>What does this mean?**<n><n>*The example sentence could be rephrased as "You can ask your friends..." but it doesn't make much sense here.<n><n><n>**You can figure it out.**<n><n>**4:** A - nature<n><n>**5:** C - great oceans<n>```<n>For example:<n>When someone thinks of the ocean, they usually think of it as a place to go on vacation, not a place to stay.<n>If the person is sick of the confines (limits) of their apartment, they will want to go somewhere else.**<n>If you want to go somewhere you can see great animals, you should go see them at the [Great Ocean Road], a place I just made up, but is probably not real.<n>Why? What are you supposed to infer from that question?<n><n>**You can make the same inference from other questions with the same structure:<n>This means that we can infer from each of these examples that the answers are the places I just made up, unless, of course, you happen to know something about them I dont know. For example, it could mean that I know which is the Great Ocean Road in Australia, but it really means that I was

Choices:  A: fraternity house B: bank C: big town D: big city E: building<n>Output:		C: big city <n>#!/usr/bin/python<n># -*- coding:utf-8 -*- <n>import pandas as pd<n>import numpy as np<n>d = pd.DataFrame({'name':['Bradley','Mike','Lane'],'gender':['male','Mike'M','Lane','Warren','Bradsley','Dorothy'],'location':['mia','mia','NYC','Denver','Phoenix','Hawaii','Jerusalem'],'age':[29, 43, 41, 27,43,44,39]})<n>d.head()<n><n>def finder(df_dict):<n>    age_list = set()<n>    gender_list = d['gender'].tolist()<n>    for age in df_dict['age']:<n>        for gender in gender_list:<n>            age_list.add(str(age))<n>    return age_list,gender_list<n><n><n><n>age_list,gender_dict = finder(d)<n>age_list<n>#finding gender list<n>gender_list = list(gender_dict.keys())<n>for i in gender_list:                                                                                                          <n>    d['gender'] = d['gender'].replace(i,' ')<n>    if list(str(d['gender'])=="male  "or "mia  "):<n>        d = d.drop('gender', axis=1)                                                                                               <n>                                                                <n>                                                #drop gender<n>#print(d.loc[4,'location'].value_counts())<n>print("age: {},".format(len(age_list))+".".join(gender_list))<n>#finding location lists<n>location_list = set()                                                                                             <n>for age in age_list.values():                                                                                            <n>    location_list.update(d['location'].findall(str(age)))                                                                      <n>#print(len(location_list),'.'.join(location_list))<n>for item in location_list:<n>    d.drop('location', axis=1)          <n>    <n>    <n>    <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The lab results had been compiled, the scientist began analysing the data because he wanted what?
